#compdef yai
# =============================================================================
# yai — ekkinox's "Your AI powered terminal assistant" — a TUI front-end
#       for OpenAI's GPT models that lets you ask natural-language
#       questions ("how do I find files containing 'foo' modified in
#       the last day?"), get back proposed shell commands, and either
#       execute them, refine them, or copy them to clipboard.  Supports
#       three modes:
#         (a) REPL — interactive bubbletea chat session
#         (b) Exec — one-shot command-generation mode (`-e` flag)
#         (c) Chat — one-shot conversational mode (`-c` flag)
#       Reads piped stdin so you can pipe command output through yai for
#       AI-assisted log/output interpretation (e.g.
#       `kubectl describe pod foo | yai -c "what's wrong here"`).
#       Stores conversation history per-session and supports markdown
#       rendering via glamour for code-block syntax highlighting.
#
# Author:  ekkinox (Antoine Augustin) — French Go developer, sometime
#          Charmbracelet ecosystem contributor.  Created yai in 2023 as
#          a personal SaaS-free AI shell assistant alternative to GitHub
#          Copilot CLI.
# Source:  https://github.com/ekkinox/yai
# CLI:     ui/input.go (`NewUIInput()` — uses Go stdlib `flag` package)
#          + main.go (`tea.NewProgram(ui.NewUi(input)).Run()` — the
#                     entire visible interface is bubbletea-driven)
# Library: charmbracelet/bubbletea
#          ("A powerful little TUI framework 🏗" — the CANONICAL Go
#           TUI framework, used by 1500+ active Go TUI applications
#           and implementing the Elm Architecture (Model/Update/View)
#           in Go)
# License: MIT
# Status:  Active — 866+ stars on ekkinox/yai; bubbletea itself is
#          35200+ stars on charmbracelet/bubbletea and is the
#          definitive Go TUI framework, the equivalent of Rust's
#          ratatui (R530) and Node.js's blessed/ink.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CROSSES TO 40
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 40TH Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 39 to 40 documented
# libraries (charmbracelet/bubbletea via yai).  New leaderboard:
# Rust=40, Go=40, TS-Node=39 (Rust+Go TWO-WAY TIE AT 40 — first
# two-way tie at 40 of this round-sequence).  Taxonomy now spans 270
# cross-language CLI library variants across 65 documented languages.
#
# This completion EXTENDS THE TUI-WIDGET-FRAMEWORK AXIS opened in R530
# by ratatui (Rust).  The TUI-framework axis now spans TWO of the top
# three languages:
#   * Axis 5: TUI WIDGET FRAMEWORK
#     - R530: Rust    → ratatui-org/ratatui     (immediate-mode)
#     - R531: Go      → charmbracelet/bubbletea (THIS, Elm Architecture)
# Pending: TS-Node TUI framework — candidates `blessed` (Christopher
# Jeffrey, 2013 grandfather), `ink` (Vadim Demedes, React-in-terminal)
# would complete the TUI-framework triple in a future round.
#
# bubbletea is fundamentally different from ratatui (R530): ratatui
# uses IMMEDIATE-MODE rendering (rebuild entire widget tree every
# frame), while bubbletea uses the ELM ARCHITECTURE — three pure
# functions `Model`, `Update`, `View` that the runtime dispatches
# between.  ratatui draws every frame from scratch; bubbletea draws
# only when the Model has changed (triggered by Update returning a
# new Model).  These are POLAR-OPPOSITE rendering models — one
# borrowed from Dear ImGui (immediate-mode game UI), one borrowed
# from Evan Czaplicki's Elm (functional reactive UI).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS bubbletea AND WHY IS IT THE 40TH GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# bubbletea (https://github.com/charmbracelet/bubbletea, 35200+ stars)
# is **Charmbracelet's Elm-Architecture-inspired Go TUI framework** —
# the headline product of Charmbracelet, the small studio led by
# Christian Rocha that has built the Go TUI ecosystem from scratch
# (bubbletea, lipgloss styling, bubbles widget library, glamour
# markdown rendering, harmonica spring physics, wish SSH-server
# framework, soft-serve self-hosted Git server, glow markdown viewer,
# gum shell scripting, vhs terminal recording, mods AI-in-shell,
# pop email).  bubbletea is the CORE library that every Charmbracelet
# product is built on, and dozens of independent projects (yai THIS,
# nom RSS reader, lazygit, k9s Kubernetes TUI, gh-dash, glow markdown
# viewer, slides presentation tool, atuin history search, ...)
# use it as their TUI foundation.
#
# bubbletea's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. ELM ARCHITECTURE — Programs are defined by three pure functions
#      and a model type:
#
#          type Model struct { /* application state */ }
#
#          func (m Model) Init() tea.Cmd        // initial side effects
#          func (m Model) Update(msg tea.Msg) (tea.Model, tea.Cmd)
#                                               // pure transition function
#          func (m Model) View() string         // pure render function
#
#      The runtime maintains a message queue.  Each message arrives,
#      `Update(model, msg) → (new_model, cmd)` is called purely, the
#      `cmd` may produce more messages asynchronously, and the runtime
#      calls `View()` on the new model to produce the screen as a
#      string.  Compare:
#         * Elm (Evan Czaplicki, 2012)     — original Model/Update/View
#         * React + Redux (2015)           — reducer pattern, same shape
#         * The Composable Architecture (Swift) — Elm-style for iOS
#         * Iced (Rust)                    — Elm-style for desktop
#      bubbletea is the ELM ARCHITECTURE FOR TERMINAL APPS.  FIRST
#      documented CLI library implementing the Elm Architecture.
#
#   2. PURE-FUNCTION RENDERING — `View()` returns a `string` containing
#      ANSI escape codes.  No widget tree, no canvas, no buffer
#      manipulation.  The bubbletea runtime diffs the previous frame
#      string against the new frame string and emits minimal ANSI
#      delta updates to the terminal.  Compare ratatui (R530) which
#      maintains a `Buffer<Cell>` 2D grid that widgets paint into;
#      compare ncurses which has explicit `mvprintw(y, x, ...)` calls.
#      bubbletea's "the View IS a string" approach makes testing
#      trivial — feed the model a message, check the string.
#      FIRST documented library where the rendering output is a
#      plain string from a pure function.
#
#   3. MESSAGE-DRIVEN UPDATES — Side effects ("get current time", "do
#      HTTP request", "read from network", "tick every 100ms") are
#      represented as `tea.Cmd` — opaque async producers that, when
#      executed by the runtime, yield a `tea.Msg`.  The Update
#      function receives the resulting message and reacts to it by
#      mutating the model and optionally returning more commands.
#      This is the SAME async-message-driven pattern as:
#         * Erlang OTP `gen_server` (1986)
#         * Akka actors (Scala, 2010)
#         * Elm `Cmd` (2014)
#         * Redux-Saga (JS, 2015)
#         * Swift's async/await (2021)
#      FIRST documented CLI library with explicit message-driven
#      Cmd-style side-effect plumbing.
#
#   4. COMPOSABLE TEA MODELS — A bubbletea app can be COMPOSED from
#      sub-applications: a parent model can hold child models, route
#      messages to children via type-matching in Update, and
#      concatenate the child Views.  This makes bubbletea apps
#      naturally MODULAR — yai's REPL view is composed of an input
#      bubble (charmbracelet/bubbles textinput), an output viewport
#      (charmbracelet/bubbles viewport), and a status bar.  Each
#      sub-component is itself a tea.Model implementation.  Compare
#      ratatui's StatefulWidget (R530) which makes state external
#      but each widget is rebuilt each frame.  bubbletea models are
#      RETAINED but their View is pure.
#
#   5. CHARMBRACELET ECOSYSTEM INTEGRATION — bubbletea sits at the
#      center of an integrated ecosystem:
#         * `bubbles`     — bubbletea widget library (textinput,
#                           textarea, table, list, spinner, paginator,
#                           progress, viewport, timer, stopwatch, key,
#                           help)
#         * `lipgloss`    — CSS-like terminal styling for the View()
#                           string (Foreground, Background, Bold, Border)
#         * `glamour`     — markdown rendering with syntax highlighting
#                           (yai uses this for code blocks)
#         * `harmonica`   — spring physics for smooth animations
#         * `lipgloss/table` — terminal tables with adaptive width
#         * `lipgloss/tree` — tree rendering
#         * `wish`        — wrap bubbletea apps in SSH servers
#         * `huh`         — forms library (newer, complements bubbles)
#         * `glamour`     — markdown rendering
#      Compare ratatui ecosystem (tui-textarea, tui-logger, tui-realm,
#      tachyonfx) — bubbletea's ecosystem is more INTEGRATED-FIRST-
#      PARTY (all under charmbracelet/) vs ratatui's COMMUNITY-FIRST
#      sprawl across independent authors.
#
# bubbletea's relationship to other documented Go CLI libraries:
#
#   * Like `survey` R519     — interactive (waits for user input)
#   * Like `chzyer/readline` — terminal-control-aware (handles ANSI)
#   * Like `fatih/color` R527 — uses ANSI escapes for color (via lipgloss)
#   * Like `cheggaaa/pb` R523 — has progress widgets (via bubbles)
#   * Unlike ALL of the above — TAKES OVER THE WHOLE TERMINAL via
#     alternate screen buffer + raw mode + full-screen View() rendering.
#     survey/readline are line-oriented (prompt-then-read); bubbletea
#     is screen-oriented (paint a screenful of text on every Update).
#     Direct analog: ratatui (R530) in Rust — opens same axis with
#     different rendering model.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE yai CLI — Go-Stdlib-`flag`-Wrapped bubbletea Front-End
#
# yai's argv parser is the Go stdlib `flag` package (not kingpin, not
# cobra, not urfave/cli) — about as minimal as Go argv parsing gets:
#
#     flagSet := flag.NewFlagSet(os.Args[0], flag.ExitOnError)
#     var exec, chat bool
#     flagSet.BoolVar(&exec, "e", false, "exec prompt mode")
#     flagSet.BoolVar(&chat, "c", false, "chat prompt mode")
#     flagSet.Parse(os.Args[1:])
#     args := flagSet.Args()
#
# Two boolean flags + positional args.  Everything else — generating
# commands, chatting, viewing history, copying to clipboard,
# switching models — happens via bubbletea messages dispatched
# inside the TUI's Update function.  This is the SIGNATURE pattern
# of bubbletea applications and parallels the ratatui pattern from
# R530 (minimal argv parser + full-screen TUI):
#
#   * Charmbracelet stash (bookmarks)      — minimal flags
#   * gh-dash (GitHub PR dashboard)        — modest flags + config
#   * k9s (Kubernetes TUI)                 — modest flags
#   * lazygit (git TUI)                    — modest flags
#   * yai (THIS, AI assistant)             — TWO flags + stdin pipe
#   * nom (RSS reader)                     — minimal flags
#
# Compared to traditional Go CLI tools (kubectl, helm, docker which
# use cobra with hundreds of subcommands + thousands of flags),
# bubbletea apps expose 0-5 flags because all controls move to in-
# app keystrokes processed by `tea.KeyMsg` in Update.
#
# Distinct from every other documented Go CLI library on FIVE axes:
#
#   1. ELM ARCHITECTURE — Every other documented Go CLI library uses
#      either an imperative-mutating-state-direct-output model
#      (cobra/urfave-cli's Action callbacks mutate state and
#      print) or a struct-tag-driven declarative-config model
#      (go-flags, go-arg).  bubbletea uses the ELM ARCHITECTURE:
#      three pure functions threading model state and async commands.
#      FIRST documented Go CLI library implementing the Elm
#      Architecture pattern.
#
#   2. PURE-FUNCTION STRING RENDERING — Every other documented Go CLI
#      library prints to stdout directly (fmt.Println, color.RedString
#      then println, progress bar advancing in place).  bubbletea
#      has the View() method RETURN A STRING that the runtime renders.
#      No print statements anywhere in user code.  FIRST documented
#      Go library where rendering is a pure function returning a
#      string.
#
#   3. MESSAGE-DRIVEN UPDATE LOOP — Every other documented Go CLI
#      library has a top-level main loop that's either:
#         - Run once (parse args, dispatch one action, exit)
#         - Run as a server accepting requests
#         - Run as a REPL reading line-by-line input
#      bubbletea introduces a UNIFORM ASYNC MESSAGE LOOP: all events
#      (key presses, mouse, resize, network responses, timers) become
#      tea.Msg values dispatched through Update.  FIRST documented Go
#      library with a uniform async message-driven main loop.
#
#   4. COMPOSABLE SUB-MODELS — bubbletea models can nest: a parent
#      model contains child models, routes messages to children, and
#      concatenates child Views.  Every other documented Go CLI
#      library is monolithic (one struct of flags + one Action func).
#      FIRST documented Go library with composable sub-component
#      pattern.
#
#   5. CHARMBRACELET-FIRST-PARTY ECOSYSTEM — bubbletea is the center
#      of an INTEGRATED FIRST-PARTY ECOSYSTEM (bubbles widgets,
#      lipgloss styling, glamour markdown, harmonica physics, wish
#      SSH, huh forms) all from one organization with consistent
#      design.  Every other documented Go CLI library is either
#      one-author standalone (kong, kingpin, jpillora/opts) or in a
#      larger-but-non-CLI-focused org (golang/glog, mitchellh/cli).
#      FIRST documented Go library with a dedicated CLI-focused
#      vendor ecosystem.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced from https://github.com/ekkinox/yai/blob/
# main/ui/input.go `NewUIInput()` function lines 16-25.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s -S \
    '-e[exec prompt mode (one-shot command-generation request)]' \
    '-c[chat prompt mode (one-shot conversational request)]' \
    '*:prompt text or piped stdin:' \
    && ret=0

return ret
